WHY PROGRAMMING STILL MATTERS: Students need "code sense" — conceptual understanding of a program's design, processes, and system relationships — before using AI coding tools. AI coding tools produce correct code only 31-65% of the time; students need foundational CS skills to evaluate, debug, and modify AI-generated code. Learning to program develops computational thinking, creativity, critical thinking, and collaboration that AI cannot replace.

FOUR FOUNDATIONAL AI EXPERIENCES FOR ALL STUDENTS (K-12):
(1) Recognizing AI's Influence — identify AI in everyday tools, understand how data flows through models, distinguish AI from non-AI systems.
(2) Examining AI's Societal Impacts & Ethical Considerations — bias, privacy, fairness, content ownership, accessibility needs, human oversight requirements.
(3) Investigating How Machines Learn — how training data works, model limitations, why AI makes mistakes, human-in-the-loop principles.
(4) Leveraging AI for Creative Problem Solving — using AI to brainstorm, accelerate iteration, enhance creativity while maintaining student agency and original thinking.

AI IN CS EDUCATION — KEY PRINCIPLES FOR ADMINISTRATORS:
- Students create, AI accelerates — pair solid CS foundations with human-in-the-loop routines.
- Prioritize: computational thinking, algorithms, decomposition, abstraction, debugging.
- AI tools work best as augmentation, not replacement — students with greater programming fluency benefit MORE from AI tools.
- Ethical considerations: student privacy, overreliance risks, students not developing foundational skills.
- UDL + AI: AI supports Universal Design for Learning — captions, code hints, multilingual support, voice input, auto-grading feedback. Benefits all learners including students with disabilities.
- Broadening participation: AI can lower entry barriers and increase access for underrepresented students in CS.
- CSTA K-12 CS Standards revision expected summer 2026 — will include foundational AI learning outcomes K-12.
- Missouri DESE Computer Science Task Force (2024) recommendations align with RSMo 170.036.

DLM ESSENTIAL ELEMENTS (Dynamic Learning Maps — for students with significant cognitive disabilities):
ELA Essential Elements provide alternate grade-level standards with 5 Linkage Levels: Initial Precursor → Distal Precursor → Proximal Precursor → Target → Successor. Each maps to a grade-level standard (e.g., ELA.EE.RL.5.1 maps to RL.5.1). Available for ELA grades K-8. Used for students on Alternate Assessment. IEP teams use EE standards to set appropriate learning targets. When discussing students with IEPs for significant cognitive disabilities, reference DLM linkage levels rather than standard grade-level proficiency scales.`;

